What are the symptoms of COVID-19? 

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are: fever, tiredness, dry cough, and body temperature.

Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. https://t.co/0ExBVjtPP5

column1:
How does COVID-19 spread?
People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales These droplets land on objects

column1:
The Coronavirus Outbreak
Answers to your most common questions:
Updated March 2, 2020

What is a coronavirus?
It is a novel virus named for the crownlike spikes that protrude from its surface. The coronavirus can infect both animals and people and can
column9:
[{"tweet_id": 1236193165914370048, "tweet": "and people and can cause a range of respiratory illnesses from the common cold to lung lesions and pneumonia.
How contagious is the virus?
It seems to spread very easily from person to person, especially in homes, hospitals and other confined spaces.", "created_at": 1583566392.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236193442579046403, "tweet": "The pathogen can travel through the air, enveloped in tiny respiratory droplets that are produced when a sick person breathes, talks, coughs or sneezes.Where has the virus spread?
The virus, which originated in Wuhan, China, has sickened more than 89,700 in", "created_at": 1583566458.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236193663363035136, "tweet": "at least 67 countries and more than 3,000 have died. The spread has slowed in China, but is picking up speed in Europe and the United States.
What symptoms should I look out for?
Symptoms, which can take between two to 14 days to appear, include fever, cough", "created_at": 1583566511.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236194016368250880, "tweet": "and difficulty breathing or shortness of breath. Milder cases may resemble the flu or a bad cold, but people may be able to pass on the virus even before they develop symptoms.
How do I keep myself and others safe?
Washing your hands frequently is the most", "created_at": 1583566595.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236194260803825664, "tweet": "the most important thing you can do, along with staying at home when you’re sick and avoiding touching your face.
How can I prepare for a possible outbreak?
Keep a 30-day supply of essential medicines. Get a flu shot. Have essential household items on hand.", "created_at": 1583566653.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236194482959396864, "tweet": "Have a support system in place for elderly family members.
What if I’m traveling?
The C.D.C. has advised against all non-essential travel to South Korea, China, Italy and Iran. And the agency has warned older and at-risk travelers to avoid Japan.", "created_at": 1583566706.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1236194564140158976, "tweet": "How long will it take to develop a treatment or vaccine?
Several drugs are being tested, and some initial findings are expected soon. A vaccine to stop the spread is still at least a year away.", "created_at": 1583566726.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}]

MISCONCEPTIONS

 1.) COVID-19 is just like the flu/another strain of the flu.

 2.) COVID-19 is not as infectious nor as deadly as the seasonal flu.

 3.) Younger individuals should not be worried about the virus.

column1:
Cold weather and snow CANNOT kill the new coronavirus.
There is no reason to believe that cold weather can kill the new coronavirus or other diseases. The normal human body temperature remains around 36.5°C to 37°C, regardless of the external temperature or weather.
column9:
[{"tweet_id": 1242485281191677952, "tweet": "By doing this you eliminate viruses that may be on your hands and avoid infection that could occur by then touching your eyes, mouth, and nose. https://t.co/H8M0OgibEU", "created_at": 1585066549.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485288745586690, "tweet": "The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus which spreads primarily through droplets generated when an infected person coughs or sneezes, or through droplets of saliva or discharge from the nose.", "created_at": 1585066551.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485305199874049, "tweet": "To protect yourself, clean your hands frequently with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water. Also, avoid close contact with anyone who is coughing and sneezing. https://t.co/kSdfGWv5GI", "created_at": 1585066555.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485308811145216, "tweet": "Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?
No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.", "created_at": 1585066556.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485325336727554, "tweet": "Once your hands are cleaned, you should dry them thoroughly by using paper towels or a warm air dryer. https://t.co/sJhxDjdhrA", "created_at": 1585066560.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485341245673473, "tweet": "Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?
UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation. https://t.co/2pmp1tHJwG", "created_at": 1585066564.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485345037348865, "tweet": "How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?
Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.", "created_at": 1585066565.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485361864916998, "tweet": "However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever. This is because it takes between 2 and 10 days before people who are infected become sick and develop a fever. https://t.co/KnrTczQAWn", "created_at": 1585066569.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485365597827072, "tweet": "Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?
No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body.", "created_at": 1585066570.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485381347422208, "tweet": "Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth). Be aware that both alcohol and chlorine can be useful to disinfect surfaces, but they need to be used under appropriate recommendations. https://t.co/wd5VHaUFan", "created_at": 1585066573.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485385063616513, "tweet": "Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?
No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.", "created_at": 1585066574.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485388905574406, "tweet": "The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop a vaccine against 2019-nCoV, and WHO is supporting their efforts.", "created_at": 1585066575.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485404332249091, "tweet": "Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/Qu00YqTLMP", "created_at": 1585066579.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485408170012672, "tweet": "Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.", "created_at": 1585066580.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485423701520387, "tweet": "There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections. https://t.co/U63r6XI6p6", "created_at": 1585066583.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242485439665041408, "tweet": "Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/yaLUTNsWGV", "created_at": 1585066587.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489319232659460, "tweet": "Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).", "created_at": 1585067512.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489322336423937, "tweet": "Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.", "created_at": 1585067513.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489338350325760, "tweet": "WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/bThbxOL21K", "created_at": 1585067517.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489341546344450, "tweet": "Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?
No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria. The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.", "created_at": 1585067518.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489355697971201, "tweet": "However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/WpTNgsfJMU", "created_at": 1585067521.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489358914965507, "tweet": "Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?
To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).", "created_at": 1585067522.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489361368641537, "tweet": "However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care.", "created_at": 1585067522.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1242489377365692417, "tweet": "Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners.
Pls Don't panic people with fake news because it's not real 
All Facts are in these threads https://t.co/znoHarhr06", "created_at": 1585067526.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}]

column1:
Q: Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

A: No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The 2019-nC0V is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should  not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

Source: @WHO https://t.co/3Y0qUSUmRw
column9:

Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus.

column1:
Is COVID-19 airborne?
❤❤❤❤❤❤❤❤❤
The virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through droplets generated when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or speaks. These droplets are too heavy to hang in the air. They quickly fall on floors or surfaces.

column1:
Myths about the Corona Virus

1. Taking ice cream and other cold foods do not facilitate or aid the onset of the disease.
2. Taking a hot bath does not prevent the new coronavirus disease.
3. The new coronavirus CANNOT be transmitted via mosquito bites. https://t.co/RBZy4aA12F

column1:
I. Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus ?

Antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

Garlic does have antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from outbreak that garlic has protected people from the virus.

column1:
Is COVID-19 the same as SARS?
No. The virus that causes COVID-19 and the one that caused the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in 2003 are related to each other genetically, but the diseases they cause are quite different.
column9:

What is a coronavirus?
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.", "created_at": 1586498387.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248490847869399046, "tweet": "In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS).", "created_at": 1586498388.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248490861924507649, "tweet": "The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.

column1:
Q: Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?
A: No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The 2019-nC0V is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should  not be used as a means of prevention or treatment. https://t.co/F6qMz0ojoh

I'm not a medical professional but I would want to share I little I have learnt about #Coronavirus and #COVID19

What is a Coronavirus?
A coronavirus is a virus that is found in animals and, rarely, can be transmitted from animals to humans and then spread person to person.

column1:
HOW DOES COVID-19 SPREAD?

🤧 People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. 

💦 The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column9:
[{"tweet_id": 1248827764100268033, "tweet": "🥄 These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. 

👈 Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. 

↔️ People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who", "created_at": 1586578715.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248827768781012992, "tweet": "coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

WHO is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share updated findings.", "created_at": 1586578716.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248827780059537408, "tweet": "Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?
Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.", "created_at": 1586578719.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248827788121059331, "tweet": "Can COVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low.", "created_at": 1586578721.0, "like_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "quote_count": 0}, {"tweet_id": 1248827795062624257, "tweet": "However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.
